hands_on_practices.solution:
We work in cylindrical coordinates $(r,\theta,z)$ with $\vec B=B_\theta(r)\,\hat e_\theta+B_{z0}\,\hat e_z$ and $p=p(r)$.  Equilibrium gives
1) Ampère’s law (static):  
$$\nabla\times\vec B=\mu_0\vec J
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
J_z=\frac1{\mu_0r}\frac{d\bigl(rB_\theta\bigr)}{dr},\quad J_r=J_\theta=0.$$
2) MHD force balance in the radial direction:  
$$\frac{dp}{dr}=(\vec J\times\vec B)_r
=-J_z\,B_\theta
=-\frac{B_\theta}{\mu_0r}\frac{d(rB_\theta)}{dr}.$$
Substitute $p(r)=p_0(1-r^2/a^2)$ so $dp/dr=-2p_0r/a^2$:
$$-\frac{2p_0r}{a^2}
=-\frac{B_\theta}{\mu_0r}\frac{d(rB_\theta)}{dr}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{B_\theta}{\mu_0r}\frac{d(rB_\theta)}{dr}
=\frac{2p_0r}{a^2}.$$
Multiply by $\mu_0r$ and set $f(r)=rB_\theta$:
$$f'(r)=\frac{df}{dr},\qquad
B_\theta=\frac{f}{r},$$
so
$$\frac{f}{r}\,\frac{df}{dr}
=\frac{2\mu_0p_0\,r^2}{a^2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
f\,\frac{df}{dr}
=\frac{2\mu_0p_0\,r^3}{a^2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{d(f^2)}{dr}
=\frac{4\mu_0p_0\,r^3}{a^2}.$$
Integrate from $0$ to $r$, using $f(0)=0$:
$$f^2(r)
=\int_0^r\frac{4\mu_0p_0\,r'^3}{a^2}dr'
=\frac{4\mu_0p_0}{a^2}\,\frac{r^4}{4}
=\frac{\mu_0p_0\,r^4}{a^2}.$$
Hence 
$$r^2B_\theta^2=f^2
=\frac{\mu_0p_0\,r^4}{a^2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
B_\theta(r)
=\sqrt{\mu_0p_0}\,\frac{r}{a}.$$
